"Wang Y.-P., Houlton B.Z.","Nitrogen constraints on terrestrial carbon uptake: Implications for the global carbon-climate feedback",2009,"Geophysical Research Letters","36","24", L24403,"","",,,10.1029/2009GL041009,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-75649146196&partnerID=40&md5=d2dd48315b8a1856308512aae8ca07f2","CSIRO Marine and Atmospheric Research, CAWCR, Aspendale, VIC, Australia; Department of Land, Air and Water Resources, University of California, One Shields Ave, Davis, CA 95616, United States; CSIRO Marine and Atmospheric Research, Private Bag 1, Aspendale, VIC 3195, Australia","Wang, Y.-P., CSIRO Marine and Atmospheric Research, CAWCR, Aspendale, VIC, Australia, CSIRO Marine and Atmospheric Research, Private Bag 1, Aspendale, VIC 3195, Australia; Houlton, B.Z., Department of Land, Air and Water Resources, University of California, One Shields Ave, Davis, CA 95616, United States","Carbon-climate feedback has been identified as one of the key areas of synthesis for the next Inter-governmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC); however, most of the models on which the IPCC will rely are yet to consider vital interactions between nitrogen (N) and carbon (C) cycles. A major impediment to including N limitation in model predictions has been the lack of constraint to rates of N fixation worldwide. Here we use a theoretical framework that considers interactions of C and nutrients to estimate rates of terrestrial N fixation, and thereby examining how the constraints of N on land C uptake and global warming. We show that most global models without nutrient limitations significantly overestimated land C uptake, thus underestimating both the pace and magnitude of the predicted global warming. We suggest that the next IPCC assessment should consider nutrient constraints on carbon-climate feedback and the pace of global warming. Copyright 2009 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Carbon uptake; Global models; Model prediction; N-fixation; Nutrient limitations; Theoretical framework; Global warming; Nutrients; Climate models; carbon cycle; climate feedback; global warming; Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change; nitrogen cycle; nitrogen fixation; nutrient dynamics",,,,,,"Dentener, F.J., (2006) Global Maps of Atmospheric Nitrogen Deposition, 1860, 1993 and 2050, , http://daac.ornl.gov, Oak Ridge Natl, Lab. Distrib. Act. Arch. Cent, Oak Ridge, Tenn; Cleveland, C.C., Global patterns of terrestrial biological nitrogen (N2) fixation in natural systems (1999) Global Biogeochem. Cycles, 13, pp. 623-645. , doi:10.1029/1999GB900014; Friedlingstein, P., Climate-carbon cycle feedback analysis: Results from the C4MIP model intercomparison (2006) J. Clim., 19, pp. 3337-3353. , doi: 10.1175/JCLI3800.1; Hibbard, K.A., Meehl, G.A., Cox, P.M., Friedlingstein, P., A strategy for climate change stabilization experiments (2007) Eos Trans. AGU, 88 (20). , doi: 10.1029/2007EO200002; Houlton, B.Z., Wang, Y.P., Vitousek, P.M., Field, C.B., A unifying framework for dinitrogen fixation in the terrestrial biosphere (2008) Nature, 454, pp. 327-330. , doi:10.1038/nature07028; Hungate, B.A., Dukes, J.S., Shaw, R., Luo, Y.Q., Field, C.B., Nitrogen and climate change (2003) Science, 302, pp. 1512-1513. , doi: 10.1126/science.1091390; Hungate, B.A., CO2 elicits long-term, decline in nitrogen fixation (2004) Science, 304, p. 1291. , doi:10.1126/soienoe.l095549; Luo, Y.Q., Progressive nitrogen limitation of ecosystem responses to rising atmospheric carbon dioxide (2004) BioScience, 54, pp. 731-739. , doi: 10.1641/0006-3568(2004)054[0731 :PNLOER]2.0.CO;2; Sokolov, A.P., Kicklighter, D.W., Melillo, J.M., Felzer, B.S., Consequences of considering carbon-nitrogen interactions on the feed-backs between climate and the terrestrial carbon cycle (2008) J. Clim., 21, pp. 3776-3796. , doi:10.1175/2008JCLI2038.1; Ter Steege, H., Continental-scale patterns of canopy tree composition and function across Amazonia (2006) Nature, 443, pp. 444-447. , doi:10.1038/nature05134; Thornton, P.E., Lamarque, J.-F., Rosenbloom, N.A., Mahowald, N.M., Influence of carbon-nitrogen coupling on land model response to CO 2 fertilization, and climate variability (2007) Global Biogeochem. Cycles, 21, pp. GB4018. , doi:10.1029/2006GB002868; Van Groenigen, K.J., Six, J., Hungate, B.A., De Graaf, M.A., Van Breemen, N., Van Kessel, C., Element interactions limit soil carbon storage (2006) Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A., 103, pp. 6571-6574. , doi:10.1073/pnas.0509038103; Vitousek, P.M., Howarth, R.W., Nitrogen, limitation on land and in the sea: How can it occur (1991) Biogeochemistry, 13, pp. 87-115. , doi:10.1007/BF00002772; Wang, Y.P., Houlton, B., Field, C.B., A model of biogeochem-ical cycles of carbon, nitrogen and phosphorus including symbiotic nitro-gen fixation and phosphatase production (2007) Global Biogeochem. Cycles, 21, pp. GB1018. , doi: 10.1029/2006GB002797; West, J.B., Hillerislambeis, J., Lee, T.D., Hobbie, S.E., Reich, P.B., Legume species identity and soil nitrogen supply determine symbiotic nitrogen-fixation responses to elevated atmospheric [CO2] (2005) New Phytol., 167, pp. 523-530. , doi:10.1111/j.l469-8137.2005.01444.x","Wang, Y.-P.; CSIRO Marine and Atmospheric Research, CAWCR, Aspendale, VIC, Australia; email: yingping.wang@csiro.au",,,,,,,,00948276,,GPRLA,,"English","Geophys. Res. Lett.",Article,Scopus,2-s2.0-75649146196
